{{MultipleIssues|citation|updatecontent=[[Star Wars: The Old Republic]]}}
[[File:Armorer_FDKP_Cristi_Balanescu.png|thumb|right|250px|A female [[Lannik (species)/Legends|Lannik]] Jedi Guardian in armor]]
During times of great conflict, [[Jedi/Legends|Jedi]] would sometimes require the use of '''battle armor'''. [[Armor/Legends|Armor]]-clad Jedi were a common sight on the battlefields of the [[New Sith Wars]], while the ancient Jedi of the era of the [[Old Sith Wars]] would often wear parts of armor to protect certain areas of their bodies, as would many Jedi of the New Sith Wars era. Shoulder guards were especially common among the ranks of the ancient Jedi.

Jedi armor was designed to be light and comfortable, giving the wearer as much freedom of movement as possible. However, the freedoms provided by Jedi armor were very limited compared to those provided by traditional Jedi robes. In the ancient wars between the Jedi and the [[Sith/Legends|Sith]], the battlefields were often so packed with combatants that moving about freely on the battlefield would be difficult even without armor. This would result in immobile and poorly protected combatants, which may be why the Jedi of those eras chose to prioritize armor to mobility.

Finding particular use in the [[Army of Light/Legends|Army of Light]] under [[Jedi Lord|Lord]] [[Hoth (Jedi Lord)|Hoth]] during the [[New Sith Wars]], Jedi armor was designed to be comfortable for the wearer, light and give the wearer the ability to use [[The Force/Legends|the Force]] as much as possible.

==History==
===At the time of the Pius Dea Crusades===
During the [[Pius Dea Era|Pius Dea]] and early [[Ductavis Era|Ductavis eras]], Jedi Knights wore full-body metal armor with horned helmets. This type of armor was immortalized in history, as [[Luke Skywalker/Legends|Luke Skywalker]] was familiar with it as a young man, more than 10,000 years later.<ref name="Blind Fury!">{{StoryCite|story=Blind Fury!|book=Star Wars Monthly 159}}</ref>

===During the Great Galactic War and Cold War===
[[File:JediGarment.jpg|thumb|left|150px|Jedi armor during the [[Cold War (Galactic Republic–Sith Empire)|Cold War]]]]
During the [[Great Galactic War]] and the [[Cold War (Galactic Republic–Sith Empire)|Cold War]] in the years following the [[Treaty of Coruscant]], many [[Jedi Knight/Legends|Jedi Knights]] donned parts or even entire suits of heavy armor when going into battle.

===During the Battle of Ruusan===
Throughout the New Sith Wars, Jedi would customize and modify their armors while some preferred not to wear any armor at all.

Around the time of the [[Great Galactic War]] (and at times in the later years), Jedi armor commonly had [[Kama/Legends|kamas]], whereas Sith armor had capes.

After the [[Ruusan Reformations/Legends|Ruusan Reformation]], the Jedi, having disbanded their armies, also gave up the use of the armor.

===During the Clone Wars===
[[File:Kenobi_Jedi_armor.jpg|thumb|right|[[Obi-Wan Kenobi/Legends|Obi-Wan Kenobi]] wearing modified [[Clone trooper armor/Legends|clone trooper armor]].]]
[[22 BBY/Legends|Around one thousand years later]], the [[Clone Wars/Legends|Clone Wars]] broke out. On certain occasions, Jedi, fighting side by side with [[Clone trooper/Legends|clone troopers]], would wear regular clone trooper armor. General [[Obi-Wan Kenobi/Legends|Obi-Wan Kenobi]] wore clone trooper armor in the [[Battle of Muunilinst/Legends|Battle of Muunilinst]] to protect himself from the lances of [[Durge/Legends|Durge]] and his army of [[Swoop/Legends|swoop]]-riding [[Assassin droid/Legends|assassin droids]].

During this same period, Jedi Knight [[Bardan Jusik]] was well known for wearing clone trooper armor into combat, and later on even full [[Mandalorian armor/Legends|Beskar'gam]].

Later into the war, many Jedi wore chest plate armor that resembled modified clone armor designs. [[Anakin Skywalker/Legends|Anakin Skywalker]] and [[Obi-Wan Kenobi/Legends|Obi-Wan Kenobi]] were examples of Jedi that wore these designs. Often, many Jedi continued to wear modified clone trooper gauntlets with chest plates.<ref name="Downfall of a Droid">[[Downfall of a Droid]], Decoded</ref>

===Post-Clone Wars===
After the Clone Wars, those few Jedi that survived [[Order 66/Legends|Order 66]] went into hiding so as not to fall victim to the [[Great Jedi Purge/Legends|Great Jedi Purge]]. Some of those ceased to wear traditional Jedi garments and would start wearing battle armor so as not to give themselves away as Jedi. [[Bultar Swan/Legends|Bultar Swan]], for instance, started wearing battle armor, but eventually fell victim to the Jedi Purge. Other Jedi, like [[Drake Lo'gaan/Legends|Drake Lo'gaan]], would supplement their robes with bits and pieces of clone trooper armor. A clone of Galen Marek also came into possession of a set of Hero's Armor, as well as a set of Experimental Jedi Armors developed on Kamino.

===New Jedi Order===
During the [[Yuuzhan Vong War]], some Jedi wore padded jumpsuits. [[Luke Skywalker/Legends|Luke Skywalker]] and [[Darth Caedus|Jacen Solo]] wore such jumpsuits during their mission to Belkadan early in the war.

==Behind the scenes==
In an interview [[Dan Thorsland]], editor of the [[Star Wars: Tales of the Jedi (comic series)|''Tales of the Jedi'']] comic books argues that wearing armor is not consistent with the way of the Jedi:<ref name="MSWCCA">{{JournalCite|2|Making Star Wars Comics Come Alive|Making ''Star Wars'' Comics Come Alive}}</ref>
{{Quote|You won't see Jedi wearing a lot of armor, and there's a reason for that. So we make sure no one's running around looking like King Arthur from Excalibur. That's not the way of a Jedi.|Dan Thorsland|<ref name="MSWCCA" />}}
This is in contrast with the way that the Jedi are depicted in [[Star Wars: Jedi vs. Sith|''Jedi vs. Sith'']]&mdash;set in the [[New Sith Wars]]&mdash;where most of the Jedi are armor-clad.<ref name="JS">''[[Star Wars: Jedi vs. Sith]]''</ref> Obi-Wan Kenobi and Saesee Tiin are both featured in full armor in ''[[Star Wars: Clone Wars]]'',<ref name="CW8">{{CW|8}}</ref> although Tiin's armor's primary function is that of a [[Environment suit/Legends|spacesuit]].<ref name="CW23">{{CW|23}}</ref> The ''[[Knights of the Old Republic]]'' games, on the other hand, preserve consistency with the typical Jedi apparel in that, even though Force-sensitive party members (including the player) may wear battle armor, doing so blocks the use of many [[Force power/Legends|Force powers]], such as [[Force speed/Legends|Force speed]], while others don't. This may be seen simply as a game mechanic designed to balance a Force-sensitive character's abilities, yet it is remarkably in line with Thorsland's statement about the inconsistency of armor and the way of the Jedi, though there are still armors available that don't restrict Force usage.<ref name="KOTOR">''[[Star Wars: Knights of the Old Republic]]''</ref>

The concept of [[Imperial Knight]]s seems to completely disregard this notion, since Imperial Knights' standard apparel is armor, and yet it does not restrict their use of Force powers in any way.<ref name="SWL3">[[Legacy (2006) 3|''Legacy'' (2006) 3]]</ref>

===Non-canon===
[[File:WhiteVader.jpg|thumb|left|100px|Anakin Skywalker's armor (non-canon)]]
In the non-canon ''Return of the Jedi Infinities'', Darth Vader is redeemed without dying, resulting in Anakin Skywalker having his [[Darth Vader's armor/Legends|armor]] repainted white to symbolize his return to the [[Light side of the Force/Legends|light]].

